TextChange: \"halo effect\" that allows attractive people to be seen as more important or smarter than they really are can cause a detriment to society, but I doubt that the damage done is of major concern.  Also, a lot of advertisement is visually driven in an attempt to persuade people that a less valuable item is more valuable than it otherwise should be.  However, with time and proper guidance, people can be taught(or, in the worse case, learn from experience) just what they cannot actually believe with thier own eyes.\n\nImages and impressions are important.  They have served us well throughout the lifetime of our species and I would be suspect of any attempts to curb our reliance on them.
